---
/**
 * /chain-builder/ (S22): the interactive chain builder. Pick verified THINGs,
 * wire type-checked ports, and watch the planner evaluate the whole system —
 * refusals propagating, materials cascading, every number keeping its citation.
 *
 * The catalog index handed to the island is SLIM (slug + title + taxonomy +
 * branches===null configs); the full compiled artifact and generated fns for a
 * THING load lazily in the island on node-add, so 36 artifacts (~1 MB) never sit
 * in the eager payload. The legality table below is built with the same
 * connectionLegal() the runtime planner uses — real engine verdicts as content.
 */
import { getCollection, getEntry } from "astro:content";
import ChainBuilder from "../components/ChainBuilder";
import { portOf } from "../engines/chain-eval";
import { connectionLegal } from "../engines/units";
import { CATEGORIES, spineOrdered } from "../lib/catalog";
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import { withBase } from "../lib/url";

const compiled = await getCollection("compiled");
const things = await getCollection("things");
const taxonomyBy = new Map(
  things.map((t) => [t.data.id, { category: t.data.category, topic: t.data.topic ?? null }]),
);

// buildable catalog: every THING/configuration with branches===null (multi-branch
// four-bar excluded in v1; solve1d configs INCLUDED — the browser runs Brent).
const placeables = compiled
  .map((c) => {
    const tax = taxonomyBy.get(c.data.thing);
    const configs = c.data.configurations
      .filter((cfg) => cfg.branches === null)
      .map((cfg) => ({ id: cfg.id, label: cfg.label }));
    return {
      id: c.data.thing,
      slug: c.data.thing,
      title: c.data.title,
      category: tax?.category ?? "",
      topic: tax?.topic ?? undefined,
      configs,
    };
  })
  .filter((t) => t.configs.length > 0);

const catalog = spineOrdered(placeables).map((t) => ({
  slug: t.slug,
  title: t.title,
  category: t.category,
  topic: t.topic ?? null,
  configs: t.configs,
}));
const categories = CATEGORIES.map((c) => ({ slug: c.slug, name: c.name }));
const materials = (await getCollection("materials")).map((m) => m.data);

// static legality table — real connectionLegal() verdicts over buildable THINGs
const gear = (await getEntry("compiled", "planetary-gearset"))!.data;
const shaft = (await getEntry("compiled", "torsion-shaft"))!.data;
const flywheel = (await getEntry("compiled", "flywheel-disk"))!.data;
const column = (await getEntry("compiled", "euler-column"))!.data;
// same Port constructor the runtime planner uses (invariant 4, one definition)
const checks = [
  { from: "planetary T_out — torque", to: "shaft T — torque", res: connectionLegal(portOf(gear, "T_out"), portOf(shaft, "T")) },
  { from: "planetary ω_c — angular velocity", to: "flywheel ω — angular velocity", res: connectionLegal(portOf(gear, "omega_c"), portOf(flywheel, "omega")) },
  { from: "planetary ω_c — angular velocity", to: "shaft T — torque", res: connectionLegal(portOf(gear, "omega_c"), portOf(shaft, "T")) },
  { from: "planetary N_r — tooth count", to: "column K — end-fixity ratio", res: connectionLegal(portOf(gear, "N_r"), portOf(column, "K")) },
];
---

<Base
  title="Chain builder"
  description="Wire verified THINGs into a system: pick components, connect type-checked ports, and watch the planner evaluate the whole chain with every number keeping its citation."
>
  <h1>Chain builder</h1>
  <p>
    Every machine is THINGs wired together. Pick components from the catalog, connect one THING's
    output port to another's input, and the planner evaluates the whole chain in dependency order —
    stress, twist, stored energy, and safety factors propagating from node to node. A connection is
    legal only when the SI dimension <strong>and</strong> the quantity kind both match (invariant 2),
    so a torque can never be mistaken for an energy, nor an angle for a ratio. Swap a downstream
    material and watch the numbers move; drive a node past its validity envelope and watch the
    refusal propagate — a refused value is <em>withheld</em>, never forwarded as a plausible wrong
    number (invariant 5).
  </p>
  <p class="citation">
    This is the v1 builder: forward chains only, up to six nodes, single-branch configurations. For a
    fixed worked example see the <a href={withBase("chain-demo/")}>chaining demo</a> (a planetary
    reduction driving a torsion shaft, power conserved through the wiring).
  </p>

  <div data-pagefind-ignore>
    <ChainBuilder client:load catalog={catalog} categories={categories} materials={materials} />
  </div>

  <h2>Connections are type-checked</h2>
  <p>
    A binding is legal iff the SI dimension 7-vector <strong>and</strong> the quantity kind both
    match. Dimensions alone are not enough: an angle and a Poisson ratio are both dimensionless, and
    torque shares dimensions with energy. The verdicts below come from the same
    <code>connectionLegal()</code> the builder runs when you press <em>Connect</em>:
  </p>
  <div class="table-scroll">
    <table class="material-props">
      <thead>
        <tr><th scope="col">From port</th><th scope="col">To port</th><th scope="col">Engine verdict</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {
          checks.map((c) => (
            <tr>
              <td>{c.from}</td>
              <td>{c.to}</td>
              <td>
                {c.res.ok ? (
                  <span class="chain-ok">legal</span>
                ) : (
                  <span class="chain-no">rejected — {c.res.reason}</span>
                )}
              </td>
            </tr>
          ))
        }
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p class="citation">
    The planner also rejects any binding that would close a feedback loop — cyclic solving is out of
    scope in v1 (relations are stored undirected, so a cyclic solver can be added later without
    rewriting THINGs). Everything here is computed in the browser from build-time-verified functions;
    the site remains a pure static site.
  </p>
</Base>
